{{Expand French|Le Cri de Paris|date=December 2016}} [[File:Le Cri de Paris 1913.jpg|right|thumb|Share of the ''Le Cri de Paris'' SA, issued 1. May 1913]] '''''Le Cri de Paris''''' is an illustrated French political magazine that was founded by [[Alexandre Natanson]] in 1897 and was at the beginning a supplement of ''[[La Revue Blanche]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Clement|first1=Russell T.|last2=Houzé|first2=Annick |last3=Erbolato-Ramsey|first3=Christiane|year=2004|title=A Sourcebook of Gauguin's Symbolist Followers: Les Nabis, Pont-Aven, Rose + Croix|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|page=418|isbn=9780313312052}}</ref>
''Le Cri de Paris'' title means ''The Paris [[Protest]]'' in English, but it has in French two other meanings like ''Paris Fashion'' (as in « ''le dernier cri'' », ''chic'', etc.) and ''cri'' as in ''cris de Paris'', i.e. the [[street cries]]. This ambiguous title was forged by [[Félix Fénéon]].
The magazine covered news, political articles and satire.<ref name="ety">{{cite web|title=1927 Le Cri de Paris|url=https://www.etsy.com/listing/483614449/1927-magazine-le-cri-de-paris?ref=market|work=Etsy|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> [[Juan Gris]] was one of its illustrators.<ref>{{cite book |last1=de Beaucorps |first1=Monique |last2=Ergmann|first2=Raoul|year=1998|title=Great Masters of European Painting|publisher=Harry N. Abrams|page=519|isbn=9780810941311}}</ref> It featured pro-[[Alfred Dreyfus|Dreyfus]] and [[anti-colonialist]] drawings by Hermann Paul and Ibels.<ref>{{cite book|author=Peter Brooker|title=Europe 1880 - 1940|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bvsfioiQ8k8C&pg=PA99|accessdate=18 December 2016|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-965958-6|page=99}}</ref> The magazine was subject to frequent [[Censorship in France|censorship]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Joëlle Beurier|title=Press/Journalism (France)|url=http://encyclopedia.1914-1918-online.net/article/pressjournalism_france|publisher=International Encyclopedia of the First World War|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> ''Le Cri de Paris'' ceased publication in 1940.<ref name="ety"/>
